: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  APE prefe=
rred shares</a>), and I have occasionally talked about the Overstock preced=
ent as a possible model: If you give each shareholder a dividend of one bag=
 of popcorn flavored with your secret proprietary spice mix, you will make =
life hard for short sellers who have to recreate that exact spice mix to de=
liver to stock lenders. But AMC, sensibly, has not done this: Doing weird d=
ividends to delight your shareholders is better than doing weird dividends =
to punish your short sellers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then there is MMTLP. At the Wall Street Jo=
urnal, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31735317.25=
9418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9ob3ctdGhlLXN0b2NrLXRpY2tlci1tbX=
RscC1iZWNhbWUtYW4tYW50aS13YWxsLXN0cmVldC1yYWxseWluZy1jcnktM2UyYTUxMmE_bW9kP=
Wl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8536a58f" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Alexande=
r Osipovich does the hard labor</a> of explaining it:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">MMTLP was a set of preferred shares whose valu=
e was largely underpinned by oil and gas assets in the Orogrande Basin of W=
est Texas. They were issued in 2021 when Torchlight Energy Resources, a Pla=
no, Texas-based oil company, merged with Meta Materials, a Canadian nanotec=
hnology firm. They traded in the risky OTC market until December, when they=
 were removed from circulation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In their last weeks of trading, buzz mounted t=
hat the shares were poised for a short squeeze, a phenomenon in which short=
 sellers exit their bets against a stock, causing its price to rally. Fuele=
d by such chatter, MMTLP surged more than 650% from the start of October to=
 Nov. 21. That put a peak valuation of about $2 billion on the underlying a=
ssets=E2=80=94even though some oil and gas analysts have dismissed them as =
worthless.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The catalyst for the anticipated squeeze was a=
n unusual transaction in which MMTLP shares were set to be converted into s=
hares of a new, nonpublicly traded company called Next Bridge Hydrocarbons.=
 Many investors were convinced that short sellers had placed massive, hidde=
n bets against MMTLP in the months and years before the planned conversion.=
 They expected it to trigger a last-minute scramble as shorts snapped up MM=
TLP, sending the share price surging.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Dec. 9, 2022, Finra halted trading in MMTLP=
. Such halts are part of Finra=E2=80=99s tool kit for preventing market dis=
ruptions. But the halt surprised adherents of the short-squeeze theory, who=
 expected two more days of trading in which to realize their gains.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some investors had poured tens of thousands of=
 dollars into MMTLP expecting big profits. Instead, they were stuck with sh=
ares they can=E2=80=99t sell.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CGiven the lack of drilling success, p=
roduction or cash flow at Orogrande, it is certainly possible the preferred=
 stock transaction was simply a means to create the perception or reality o=
f a short squeeze,=E2=80=9D said Jeff Davies, a former energy hedge-fund ma=
nager.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CUnfortunately the people who bought i=
nto the short-squeeze thesis and spent no time valuing the underlying asset=
s got hurt the most.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fort Worth, Texas-based Next Bridge declined t=
o comment. Meta Materials Chief Executive George Palikaras said his company=
 spun out the energy assets into a private company to protect shareholders =
from problems such as naked short selling=E2=80=94an abusive practice in wh=
ich short sellers place bets against a stock without obtaining the shares n=
eeded for the trade.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ah. There=E2=80=99s an oil company with some p=
ossibly worthless reserves. It was the subject of=C2=A0social-media <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31735317.259418/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0yMjE/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB9b87bbe9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> pump-and-dump schemes</a>. (=E2=80=9CTorchlight man=
agement wasn=E2=80=99t aware of the schemes, and no executives at Torchligh=
t or Meta Materials have been accused,=E2=80=9D reports Osipovich.) It merg=
ed with=C2=A0<em>a nanotechnology firm</em>, as one does, and put the oil a=
ssets in a new weird stock=C2=A0called MMTLP. MMTLP was a sort of tracking =
stock or contingent value right on the oil and gas assets: Holders of the p=
referred stock <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/317=
35317.259418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdG=
EvMTQzMTk1OS8wMDAwOTUwMTcwMjIwMDI2MDEvbW1hdC0yMDIxMTIzMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB2bf0ff25" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> were entitled</a> =E2=80=9Cto receive divide=
nds, or Asset Sale Dividends, comprised of the holder=E2=80=99s pro rata po=
rtion of the proceeds from the sale of the O&amp;G Assets in the event that=
 the Company consummates one or more such transaction.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That traded over the counter for a while, but =
the company never did sell the oil and gas assets. Instead, it decided to <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31735317.259418/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE5MzY3NTYvMDAwMTE5MzEyNT=
IyMjkyMTE0L2QzMDI1NzZkNDI0YjQuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB31fb2176" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> spin them out to shareholders</a>, replacing the MMTLP tracking stock w=
ith actual shares in a new oil company called Next Bridge Hydrocarbons Inc.=
 (According to its most recent=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/31735317.259418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY=
2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTkzNjc1Ni8wMDAxMTk5ODM1MjMwMDAyNDQvbmJoLTEwcS5odG0j=
YTAwM192MQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3737f780" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">quarterly report</a>,=
 Next Bridge=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccurrently has six full-time employees,=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chas not yet achieved profitable operations,=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9Chad no proved reserve value associated with our properties.=E2=80=9D)=
 Everyone=E2=80=99s MMTLP shares would automatically be converted into Next=
 Bridge common shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ordinarily, when a public company spins out a =
subsidiary to its shareholders, the subsidiary also becomes a public compan=
y: The whole point of the spinoff is to let the subsidiary=E2=80=99s shares=
 trade separately from the parent=E2=80=99s; if you are giving new stock to=
 your public shareholders, presumably they want that stock to be public too=
. But Meta specifically designed Next Bridge <em>not</em> to trade publicly=
, or at all. From <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
31735317.259418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE5MzY=
3NTYvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMjkyMTE0L2QzMDI1NzZkNDI0YjQuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cC31fb2176" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> the prospectus</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Our Common Stock is currently not =
listed for trading on any stock exchange or market and we have not sought t=
o be traded on any exchange or market. The shares of Common Stock will not =
be eligible for electronic transfer through the Depository Trust Company or=
 any other established clearing corporation. Accordingly, there currently i=
s no public trading market for the Common Stock and there is no current exp=
ectation for a public market to develop.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not only is the stock not listed on a public e=
xchange, but it is not eligible for transfer through DTC, meaning that all =
of your brokerage=E2=80=99s systems for trading the stock don=E2=80=99t wor=
k, and probably your broker won=E2=80=99t want to bother with it. (=E2=80=
=9CThe restriction was an unusual, deliberate move by Meta Materials that w=
ould effectively make the new shares untradeable,=E2=80=9D writes Osipovich=
.) =E2=80=9CAccordingly, you may have to hold the shares of Common Stock in=
definitely,=E2=80=9D says the prospectus.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is very inconvenient for MMTLP/Next Bridg=
e shareholders! Why would a company take its shareholders=E2=80=99 publicly=
 traded shares and replace them with=C2=A0<em>non-tradable=C2=A0</em>shares=
? Not because it is nice for shareholders to be unable to sell their shares=
. But because it is=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>for=C2=A0<em>short sellers=C2=A0=
</em>to be unable to=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0</em>shares. =E2=80=9CMeta Materials=
 Chief Executive George Palikaras said his company spun out the energy asse=
ts into a private company to protect shareholders from problems such as nak=
ed short selling=E2=80=9D: If nobody can sell the stock, then nobody can se=
ll the stock short; if nobody can buy the stock, then short sellers can=E2=
=80=99t buy back their shorts, and they go to prison. In the abstract, if y=
ou are a CEO who hates short sellers, =E2=80=9Cmake it so that nobody can s=
ell the stock=E2=80=9D seems like a good move. It is, however, an obviously=
 bad move=C2=A0<em>for your shareholders</em>, because they can=E2=80=99t s=
ell the stock either, oops.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The shareholders apparently didn=E2=80=99t min=
d, though, because they figured that the Next Bridge distribution would cre=
ate a short squeeze: Short sellers wouldn=E2=80=99t be able to buy Next Bri=
dge stock, so they would have to get out of their MMTLP short positions bef=
ore MMTLP was replaced by Next Bridge. And so the shareholders=C2=A0would s=
ell their MMTLP stock into the short squeeze, as the shorts were forced to =
buy, just before the spinoff was completed. In a risk factor (!), Next Brid=
ge=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31735317.2=
59418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE5MzY3NTYvMDAwM=
TE5MzEyNTIyMjkyMTE0L2QzMDI1NzZkNDI0YjQuaHRtI3RvYzMwMjU3Nl8z/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB982ac7ac" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">touted=C2=A0this possibility</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If any investors have sold shares =
of MMTLP short, then in connection with the Distribution such investors may=
 feel compelled to buy shares of MMTLP to cover such sales before the Distr=
ibution. If this were to occur, given the potential high demand from buyers=
 with a relatively low supply of MMTLP shares available for sale on the OTC=
 market, the MMTLP price per share as shown on the OTC market may rise sign=
ificantly but not be representative of the value of the underlying shares o=
f our Common Stock that you will receive in the Distribution.</p></blockquo=
te>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it didn=E2=80=99t work, the MMTLP stock wa=
s halted,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and now the people who bought it hoping that for a short squeeze =
are=C2=A0stuck holding non-tradable stock in Next Bridge. A bad result, but=
 also exactly what they were promised.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They=E2=80=99re so mad. Osipovich:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the past six months, MMTLP investors have=
 formed a noisy protest movement, wielding hashtags such as #FinraFraud. Th=
ey allege that Finra=E2=80=99s halt covered up a conspiracy among hedge fun=
ds and market makers to suppress the price of Torchlight, and later MMTLP, =
through naked short selling.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some MMTLP investors have picketed the Securit=
ies and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s headquarters in Washington, and one b=
uttonholed the agency=E2=80=99s head on Capitol Hill in April. =E2=80=A6 So=
me Finra employees and market veterans caught up in debate around MMTLP hav=
e received death threats. In one anonymous message to a market veteran seen=
 by The Wall Street Journal, the sender alluded to mass shootings and vowed=
 to come =E2=80=9Cpiss on your casket.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Charming. This is the same complaint as Patric=
k Byrne=E2=80=99s: Meta, like Overstock, tried to issue non-tradable stock =
to artificially squeeze short sellers, and it didn=E2=80=99t work, and they=
 blame the regulators for not letting it work.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My takeaways would be:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Naked short selling is an imaginary p=
roblem.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">US securities regulators t=
hink that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31735317=
.259418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAxMi0yMDEyLTE=
yMmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8cc4dca1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> engineering a short squ=
eeze is market manipulation</a>, and they are not going to=C2=A0<em>help=C2=
=A0</em>a company=E2=80=99s efforts to squeeze its shorts.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If a company is doing some baroque corporate-finan=
ce structuring with the=C2=A0<em>express purpose of hurting short sellers</=
em>, that is good news for short=C2=A0sellers and bad news for shareholders=
.</li>
</ol>
